<dl id="n06156i"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n06" href="#n06156i">N06 (VI.B.11)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n06all.htm#n06156i"> 156(i)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> groanings which cannot / be uttered <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n06156i"> <li><a href="../../flex/z/lexfh.htm#n06156i">FH XI</a> </li><li><ms href="#n06156i">MS BL 47471b-42</ms> </li><li>JJA 46:272 <a name="e30yd" href="../../FF/fdra/eda.htm#e30yd">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/e/e30yd.htm#n06156i">Draft: I.5&sect;3.0+</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">PART IV. CHRISTIAN PRAYER. <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> It is the duty of all Christians to make their wants and requests known unto God; but by nature all are weak and sinful, and unable to approach God without the special grace of the Holy Spirit. &ldquo;We know not what we should pray for as we ought; but the Spirit itself maketh intercession for us <mark>with groanings which cannot be uttered</mark>.&rdquo; The disciples of our blessed Lord, knowing their weakness, said to their Master, &ldquo;Lord, teach us to pray,&rdquo; and he gave them a <font color="green">[43]</font> pattern or model of prayer which we call the &ldquo;Lord&apos;s Prayer.&rdquo; This prayer is recorded by the evangelists St. Matthew and St. Luke. <small> Anonymous, <a name="ATCC" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#ATCC"><cite title="source">Analysis of the Church Catechism</cite></a> (1879) 43-4</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
